The paper deals with the design of low-density parity-check (LDPC) codes for non-orthogonal interleave division multiple access (IDMA) systems, which are used in wireless communication. This involves optimizing the degree profile of the LDPC code using extrinsic information transfer (EXIT) charts to match the IDMA multi-user detector. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT), Communications (cs.COMM), and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper also deals with the analytical derivation of EXIT functions for the IDMA system, which involves modeling and analysis of the system, making it likely to belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper also discusses the use of serial concatenation with a simple repetition code to design matching LDPC codes with a higher rate, which involves machine learning and optimization techniques, making it likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
